There is preliminary support for internet-delivered cognitive behaviour therapy 
(iCBT) as a way of improving access to treatment among older adults with 
anxiety. The aim of this randomized controlled trial (RCT) was to examine the 
efficacy, long-term outcomes, and cost-effectiveness of an iCBT program for 
adults over 60 years of age with anxiety. Successful applicants were randomly 
allocated to either the treatment group (n=35) or the waitlist control group 
(n=37). The online treatment course was delivered over 8 weeks and provided with 
brief weekly contact with a clinical psychologist via telephone or secure email. 
Eighty-four percent of participants completed the iCBT course within the 8 weeks 
and 90% provided data at posttreatment. Significantly lower scores on measures 
of anxiety (Cohen's d=1.43; 95% CI: 0.89 - 1.93) and depression (Cohen's d=1.79; 
